    <!-- Main jumbotron for a primary marketing message or call to action -->
    <div class="jumbotron">
      <div class="container">
        <h1><nobr>Favicons from Any Site,</nobr> <nobr>in Any Size</nobr></h1>
        <p>
          Grabicon makes it free, fast and easy to get high-quality favicons from any web site, in the size you want, instantly - even if that site doesn't provide an icon of its own.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="container">
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <h2>Free</h2>
          <p>
            Grabicon is free for developers to use in their applications. We want to be used by as many web/mobile apps as possible.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <h2>Fast</h2>
          <p>
            It can take several seconds to a retrieve a domain's favicon from scratch. We do the hard work in advance, so you get a high quality PNG image in milliseconds.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4">
          <h2>Easy</h2>
          <p>Use Grabicon directly in your image tags, like you would call any other remote image.</p>
          <p><a class="btn btn-default" href="#examples" role="button">Examples &raquo;</a></p>
       </div>
      </div>

      <hr>

      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-12">
          <a name="getting_started"></a>
          <h2>Getting Started</h2>
          <p>
            Grabicon has only one endpoint:

            <pre>http://grabicon.com/icon</pre>

            And only two parameters:

            <table class="table table-bordered">
              <tr>
                <th>parameter</th>
                <th>required?</th>
                <th>example</th>
                <th>description</th>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>domain</td>
                <td>yes</td>
                <td>wikipedia.org</td>
                <td>The domain whose favicon you want to display.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>size</td>
                <td>no</td>
                <td>32</td>
                <td>
                  The height and width of the icon to be returned. Grabicon will ensure all your icons are the size you requested, even if the website didn't originally have an icon of that size. The default is 32.
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-12">
          <a name="examples"></a>
          <h2>Examples</h2>

          <table class="table table-condensed">
            <tr>
              <td><img src="/images/icons/rubycuts.png"></td>
              <td>
                <p>The RubyCuts icon, 32 pixels. Since RubyCuts only has a 16 pixel icon available, we wrap it in a matching border to give you a consistent view from one icon to the next:</p>
                <pre>http://grabicon.com/icon?domain=rubycuts.com&amp;size=32</pre>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><img src="/images/icons/github.png"></td>
              <td>
                <p>GitHub's icon, 32 pixels, in an HTML image tag:</p>
                <pre>&lt;img src="http://grabicon.com/icon?domain=github.com&amp;size=32"&gt;</pre>
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><img src="/images/icons/example.png"></td>
              <td>
                <p>If a domain doesn't have a favicon, we create a memorable default.</p>
                <pre>http://grabicon.com/icon?domain=example.com&amp;size=32</pre>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <hr>

